1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Hello everyone, welcome back to EnglishPod. My name is Marco.
大家好，欢迎回到EnglishPod。我是Marco。

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:08,120
And I'm Erika.
我是Erika。

3
00:00:08,120 --> 00:00:14,240
And today we're bringing you again our romantic, dramatic, suspense series, I'm Sorry I Love
今天我们再次为大家带来我们的浪漫、戏剧、悬疑系列，《对不起，我爱你》

4
00:00:14,240 --> 00:00:15,820
You Part 7.
第七部分。

5
00:00:15,820 --> 00:00:20,080
So we're gonna find out what's happening with Steven and Veronica.
我们来看看Steven和Veronica之间发生了什么。

6
00:00:20,080 --> 00:00:25,400
Right, in the last episode, Veronica was at the doctor's, she was pregnant.
对，上一集里，Veronica在医生那里，她怀孕了。

7
00:00:25,400 --> 00:00:29,760
But then the doctor told her it was a lie and he made it up and she wasn't even pregnant.
但后来医生告诉她那是谎言，是他编造的，她根本没怀孕。

8
00:00:29,760 --> 00:00:30,760
Exactly.
没错。

9
00:00:30,760 --> 00:00:33,960
So now let's see what Veronica and Steven are gonna say to each other.
现在让我们看看Veronica和Steven会对彼此说什么。

10
00:00:33,960 --> 00:00:34,960
Maybe they will break up?
也许他们会分手？

11
00:00:34,960 --> 00:00:35,960
I don't know.
我不知道。

12
00:00:35,960 --> 00:00:36,960
I don't think so.
我不这么认为。

13
00:00:36,960 --> 00:00:47,440
But let's listen.
但让我们听听看。

14
00:00:47,440 --> 00:00:49,680
Thank God you showed up when you did.
谢天谢地你及时出现了。

15
00:00:49,680 --> 00:00:50,680
He's insane.
他疯了。

16
00:00:50,680 --> 00:00:53,480
Do you think we should call the police?
你觉得我们该报警吗？

17
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:54,480
Don't worry about it.
别担心。

18
00:00:54,480 --> 00:00:56,720
I'll call my friend and have him take care of it.
我会打电话给我朋友，让他处理这件事。

19
00:00:56,720 --> 00:00:58,880
I can't believe he was stalking you all these years.
真不敢相信他这些年一直在跟踪你。

20
00:00:58,880 --> 00:00:59,880
What a nutjob.
真是个疯子。

21
00:00:59,880 --> 00:01:00,880
I know.
我知道。

22
00:01:00,880 --> 00:01:03,560
Well, he said I'm not pregnant.
嗯，他说我没怀孕。

23
00:01:03,560 --> 00:01:06,640
I'm sorry if I got you all worked up over nothing.
对不起，如果我让你白激动了一场。

24
00:01:06,640 --> 00:01:09,560
I want you to know that I didn't do it on purpose.
我想让你知道我不是故意的。

25
00:01:09,560 --> 00:01:11,240
Don't apologize.
别道歉。

26
00:01:11,240 --> 00:01:15,760
From the moment I met you, not a day has gone by when I haven't thought of you.
从我遇见你的那一刻起，没有一天我不在想你。

27
00:01:15,760 --> 00:01:18,400
And now that I'm with you again, I'm just...
现在我又和你在一起了，我只是……

28
00:01:18,400 --> 00:01:19,920
I'm just scared, Veronica.
我只是害怕，Veronica。

29
00:01:19,920 --> 00:01:22,680
The closer I get to you, the worse it gets.
我越靠近你，情况就越糟。

30
00:01:22,680 --> 00:01:27,040
The thought of not being with you, I mean, I just can't handle it.
想到不能和你在一起，我的意思是，我受不了。

31
00:01:27,040 --> 00:01:29,760
We were made for each other, Veronica.
我们是天生一对，Veronica。

32
00:01:29,760 --> 00:01:30,760
You're my everything.
你是我的全部。

33
00:01:30,760 --> 00:01:31,760
My soulmate.
我的灵魂伴侣。

34
00:01:31,760 --> 00:01:34,400
What can I do?
我能做什么？

35
00:01:34,400 --> 00:01:35,400
Just hold me.
只要抱着我。

36
00:01:35,400 --> 00:01:38,400
I'll always be here for you, no matter what.
无论发生什么，我都会永远在你身边。

37
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:42,680
And together, we can tackle whatever life throws at us.
一起，我们可以应对生活抛给我们的任何挑战。

38
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:44,800
I believe in us, Steven.
我相信我们，Steven。

39
00:01:44,800 --> 00:01:47,080
I'm so happy to hear that.
听到这个我很高兴。

40
00:01:47,080 --> 00:01:48,080
I know we belong together.
我知道我们属于彼此。

41
00:01:48,080 --> 00:01:49,080
I love you so much.
我太爱你了。

42
00:01:49,080 --> 00:01:57,760
I love you so much.
我太爱你了。

43
00:01:57,760 --> 00:02:12,520
It was such a romantic moment.
那真是个浪漫的时刻。

44
00:02:12,520 --> 00:02:13,520
And now what happened?
然后发生了什么？

45
00:02:13,520 --> 00:02:14,520
Somebody got shot.
有人中枪了。

46
00:02:14,520 --> 00:02:15,520
Oh my God.
哦，我的天。

47
00:02:15,520 --> 00:02:16,520
I don't know.
我不知道。

48
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:17,520
This is like so big.
这太严重了。

49
00:02:17,520 --> 00:02:19,120
I can't believe this is happening.
真不敢相信会发生这种事。

50
00:02:19,120 --> 00:02:25,320
Well, it's a very intense drama, but we saw some great words and a lot of great phrases
嗯，这是一部非常紧张的戏剧，但我们看到了一些很棒的词语和很多精彩的短语，

51
00:02:25,320 --> 00:02:28,880
in there when Steven was telling her all these beautiful words, right?
当Steven对她说那些美丽的话时，对吧？

52
00:02:28,880 --> 00:02:29,880
That's right.
没错。

53
00:02:29,880 --> 00:02:35,640
So why don't we look at some of these words now in Language Takeaway.
那我们不如在“语言小贴士”环节看看这些词。

54
00:02:35,640 --> 00:02:38,960
Language Takeaway.
语言小贴士。

55
00:02:38,960 --> 00:02:43,680
Veronica was glad or she was very happy that Steven showed up.
Veronica很高兴，或者说她很开心Steven出现了。

56
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:44,680
That's right.
没错。

57
00:02:44,680 --> 00:02:45,680
Showed up.
出现了。

58
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:46,680
So, to show up.
所以，“出现”。

59
00:02:46,680 --> 00:02:47,680
Right.
对。

60
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:48,680
To come to a place.
来到某个地方。

61
00:02:48,680 --> 00:02:49,680
Okay.
好的。

62
00:02:49,680 --> 00:02:50,680
Or to arrive.
或者到达。

63
00:02:50,680 --> 00:02:51,680
That's right.
没错。

64
00:02:51,680 --> 00:02:56,640
So let's listen to some examples of how we can use show up in different contexts.
让我们听一些例子，看看如何在不同的语境中使用“出现”。

65
00:02:56,640 --> 00:02:59,720
Example one.
例子一。

66
00:02:59,720 --> 00:03:06,000
We were waiting for you like an hour and you never showed up.
我们等了你一个小时，你一直没出现。

67
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,320
Example two.
例子二。

68
00:03:09,320 --> 00:03:10,880
I didn't invite him to the party.
我没邀请他参加派对。

69
00:03:10,880 --> 00:03:16,320
He just simply showed up uninvited.
他就不请自来了。

70
00:03:16,320 --> 00:03:20,040
Example three.
例子三。

71
00:03:20,040 --> 00:03:24,800
After months of being lost, my dog finally showed up with a family.
失踪几个月后，我的狗终于和一个家庭一起出现了。

72
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:27,040
All right.
好的。

73
00:03:27,040 --> 00:03:29,920
So I think it's pretty clear now the verb show up.
所以我想现在动词“出现”已经很清楚了。

74
00:03:29,920 --> 00:03:33,080
And I think this verb is a little bit informal, isn't it?
我觉得这个动词有点非正式，对吧？

75
00:03:33,080 --> 00:03:34,080
Yes.
是的。

76
00:03:34,080 --> 00:03:36,280
You wouldn't really tell your boss, hey, I'm waiting for you to show up.
你不会真的对你的老板说，嘿，我在等你出现。

77
00:03:36,280 --> 00:03:37,280
Yeah.
嗯。

78
00:03:37,280 --> 00:03:38,280
Yeah.
嗯。

79
00:03:38,280 --> 00:03:39,280
It's a bit too informal.
这有点太非正式了。

80
00:03:39,280 --> 00:03:43,320
As you know, the doctor, he was stalking Veronica.
你知道，那个医生一直在跟踪Veronica。

81
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:44,320
That's right.
没错。

82
00:03:44,320 --> 00:03:45,320
So that's our next word.
所以那是我们的下一个词。

83
00:03:45,320 --> 00:03:46,320
To stalk.
跟踪。

84
00:03:46,320 --> 00:03:47,320
To stalk somebody.
跟踪某人。

85
00:03:47,320 --> 00:03:48,320
S-T-A-L-K.
S-T-A-L-K。

86
00:03:48,320 --> 00:03:49,320
Okay.
好的。

87
00:03:49,320 --> 00:03:50,320
Stalk.
跟踪。

88
00:03:50,320 --> 00:03:52,320
Now, this isn't a good thing, right?
现在，这不是好事，对吧？

89
00:03:52,320 --> 00:03:53,320
No.
不是。

90
00:03:53,320 --> 00:03:54,320
This is bad.
这是坏事。

91
00:03:54,320 --> 00:03:56,520
So what happens when you stalk someone?
那么当你跟踪某人时会发生什么？

92
00:03:56,520 --> 00:04:00,800
You follow them secretly for a long time.
你秘密地长时间跟着他们。

93
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:03,520
And then maybe you watch them and...
然后也许你观察他们，然后……

94
00:04:03,520 --> 00:04:04,520
Yeah.
嗯。

95
00:04:04,520 --> 00:04:08,560
Like you're standing outside their window watching them get undressed or something.
就像你站在他们窗外看他们脱衣服之类的。

96
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:09,560
Okay.
好的。

97
00:04:09,560 --> 00:04:11,960
So many famous people have stalkers, right?
所以很多名人都有跟踪者，对吧？

98
00:04:11,960 --> 00:04:12,960
Yeah.
嗯。

99
00:04:12,960 --> 00:04:13,960
Which is the noun.
那是名词。

100
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:14,960
The noun form, exactly.
名词形式，没错。

101
00:04:14,960 --> 00:04:18,800
So if I am stalking somebody, I am considered to be a stalker.
所以如果我跟踪某人，我就被认为是跟踪者。

102
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:19,800
Yes.
是的。

103
00:04:19,800 --> 00:04:20,800
So to stalk.
所以是“跟踪”。

104
00:04:20,800 --> 00:04:22,720
So don't do this.
所以别这么做。

105
00:04:22,720 --> 00:04:26,320
So Stephen described this stalker as a nut job.
所以Steven把这个跟踪者描述为“疯子”。

106
00:04:26,320 --> 00:04:27,320
A nut job.
疯子。

107
00:04:27,320 --> 00:04:28,320
A nut job.
疯子。

108
00:04:28,320 --> 00:04:29,320
A nut job.
疯子。

109
00:04:29,320 --> 00:04:30,320
Okay.
好的。

110
00:04:30,320 --> 00:04:35,160
Very, very informal and it doesn't really mean anything literally, but it's crazy.
非常非常非正式，字面上没什么意思，但就是“疯狂”的意思。

111
00:04:35,160 --> 00:04:36,160
Yes.
是的。

112
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:37,160
It means a crazy person.
意思是疯子。

113
00:04:37,160 --> 00:04:38,160
A crazy person.
疯子。

114
00:04:38,160 --> 00:04:39,160
What a nut job.
真是个疯子。

115
00:04:39,160 --> 00:04:40,160
He's a nut job.
他是个疯子。

116
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:41,160
Okay.
好的。

117
00:04:41,160 --> 00:04:43,920
So would you really call this to someone, like to their face?
你真的会当面这样叫别人吗？

118
00:04:43,920 --> 00:04:44,920
No.
不会。

119
00:04:44,920 --> 00:04:45,920
Definitely not.
绝对不会。

120
00:04:45,920 --> 00:04:46,920
It's definitely impolite.
这绝对不礼貌。

121
00:04:46,920 --> 00:04:47,920
Right.
对。

122
00:04:47,920 --> 00:04:49,320
You can't say to someone, oh, you're a nut job.
你不能对某人说，哦，你是个疯子。

123
00:04:49,320 --> 00:04:50,320
Yeah.
嗯。

124
00:04:50,320 --> 00:04:51,320
But it's not a swear word.
但这不是脏话。

125
00:04:51,320 --> 00:04:53,080
No, but it's a little bit insulting, right?
不是，但有点侮辱人，对吧？

126
00:04:53,080 --> 00:04:55,760
It's like saying you're crazy, but stronger.
就像说你疯了，但语气更强。

127
00:04:55,760 --> 00:04:57,680
Well, the doctor was a nut job.
嗯，那个医生是个疯子。

128
00:04:57,680 --> 00:05:03,080
He was stalking her and she apologized to Stephen for getting him worked up.
他一直在跟踪她，她为让Steven激动而道歉。

129
00:05:03,080 --> 00:05:04,120
Worked up.
激动。

130
00:05:04,120 --> 00:05:05,520
So work up.
所以是“激动”。

131
00:05:05,520 --> 00:05:06,960
To be worked up.
变得激动。

132
00:05:06,960 --> 00:05:09,360
When you get worked up, what happens?
当你变得激动时，会发生什么？

133
00:05:09,360 --> 00:05:16,200
You get really emotional and usually angry or sad or upset, but a negative emotion.
你会变得非常情绪化，通常生气、难过或沮丧，是一种负面情绪。

134
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:17,200
Okay.
好的。

135
00:05:17,200 --> 00:05:18,680
So you got worked up.
所以你激动了。

136
00:05:18,680 --> 00:05:21,120
So it's always used with the verb to get.
所以它总是和动词“变得”一起用。

137
00:05:21,120 --> 00:05:22,360
So to get worked up.
所以是“变得激动”。

138
00:05:22,360 --> 00:05:23,360
Okay.
好的。

139
00:05:23,360 --> 00:05:24,360
You get worked up.
你变得激动。

140
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:25,360
You got worked up.
你激动了。

141
00:05:25,360 --> 00:05:26,360
Okay.
好的。

142
00:05:26,360 --> 00:05:27,360
Very good.
很好。

143
00:05:27,360 --> 00:05:29,940
And well, Stephen got worked up over nothing, but he didn't mind.
嗯，Steven白激动了一场，但他并不介意。

144
00:05:29,940 --> 00:05:34,920
He said she is his love and he called her his soulmate.
他说她是他的爱，他称她为他的灵魂伴侣。

145
00:05:34,920 --> 00:05:35,920
His soulmate.
他的灵魂伴侣。

146
00:05:35,920 --> 00:05:36,920
Soulmate.
灵魂伴侣。

147
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:37,920
That's right.
没错。

148
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:42,920
That's a very romantic word, meaning the perfect person for you.
那是一个非常浪漫的词，意思是你的完美伴侣。

149
00:05:42,920 --> 00:05:43,920
Right.
对。

150
00:05:43,920 --> 00:05:44,920
Your other half.
你的另一半。

151
00:05:44,920 --> 00:05:45,920
Yes.
是的。

152
00:05:45,920 --> 00:05:46,920
Okay.
好的。

153
00:05:46,920 --> 00:05:48,880
So your soulmate is that perfect compliment for you.
所以你的灵魂伴侣是你的完美互补。

154
00:05:48,880 --> 00:05:50,840
And it's usually romantic, right?
而且通常是浪漫的，对吧？

155
00:05:50,840 --> 00:05:54,960
Usually romantic, but sometimes you might use it with your very, very, very best friend.
通常是浪漫的，但有时你可能会用它来形容你非常非常非常好的朋友。

156
00:05:54,960 --> 00:05:55,960
Okay.
好的。

157
00:05:55,960 --> 00:05:57,440
Because you understand each other.
因为你们彼此理解。

158
00:05:57,440 --> 00:05:58,440
Yeah.
嗯。

159
00:05:58,440 --> 00:05:59,440
You know what the other one's thinking.
你知道对方在想什么。

160
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:01,480
You're the perfect fit together.
你们是完美的一对。

161
00:06:01,480 --> 00:06:02,480
Okay.
好的。

162
00:06:02,480 --> 00:06:03,480
Soulmate.
灵魂伴侣。

163
00:06:03,480 --> 00:06:04,480
Very good.
很好。

164
00:06:04,480 --> 00:06:07,000
Well, we've seen some really interesting words.
嗯，我们看到了一些非常有趣的词。

165
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:11,200
So why don't we listen to our dialogue again, and then we'll come back and look at some
那我们不如再听一遍我们的对话，然后回来看看一些

166
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:18,280
of the phrases that were used.
用到的短语。

167
00:06:18,280 --> 00:06:20,520
Thank God you showed up when you did.
谢天谢地你及时出现了。

168
00:06:20,520 --> 00:06:21,520
He's insane.
他疯了。

169
00:06:21,520 --> 00:06:24,320
Do you think we should call the police?
你觉得我们该报警吗？

170
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:25,320
Don't worry about it.
别担心。

171
00:06:25,320 --> 00:06:27,600
I'll call my friend and have him take care of it.
我会打电话给我朋友，让他处理这件事。

172
00:06:27,600 --> 00:06:29,680
I can't believe he was stalking you all these years.
真不敢相信他这些年一直在跟踪你。

173
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:30,680
What a nut job.
真是个疯子。

174
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:31,680
I know.
我知道。

175
00:06:31,680 --> 00:06:34,680
Well, he said I'm not pregnant.
嗯，他说我没怀孕。

176
00:06:34,680 --> 00:06:37,760
I'm sorry if I got you all worked up over nothing.
对不起，如果我让你白激动了一场。

177
00:06:37,760 --> 00:06:40,680
I want you to know that I didn't do it on purpose.
我想让你知道我不是故意的。

178
00:06:40,680 --> 00:06:42,360
Don't apologize.
别道歉。

179
00:06:42,360 --> 00:06:46,880
From the moment I met you, not a day has gone by when I haven't thought of you.
从我遇见你的那一刻起，没有一天我不在想你。

180
00:06:46,880 --> 00:06:50,800
And now that I'm with you again, I'm just scared, Veronica.
现在我又和你在一起了，我只是害怕，Veronica。

181
00:06:50,800 --> 00:06:53,620
The closer I get to you, the worse it gets.
我越靠近你，情况就越糟。

182
00:06:53,620 --> 00:06:58,000
The thought of not being with you, I mean, I just can't handle it.
想到不能和你在一起，我的意思是，我受不了。

183
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:00,720
We were made for each other, Veronica.
我们是天生一对，Veronica。

184
00:07:00,720 --> 00:07:01,720
You're my everything.
你是我的全部。

185
00:07:01,720 --> 00:07:02,720
My soulmate.
我的灵魂伴侣。

186
00:07:02,720 --> 00:07:05,280
What can I do?
我能做什么？

187
00:07:05,280 --> 00:07:06,280
Just hold me.
只要抱着我。

188
00:07:06,280 --> 00:07:09,280
I'll always be here for you, no matter what.
无论发生什么，我都会永远在你身边。

189
00:07:09,280 --> 00:07:13,560
And together, we can tackle whatever life throws at us.
一起，我们可以应对生活抛给我们的任何挑战。

190
00:07:13,560 --> 00:07:15,600
I believe in us, Steven.
我相信我们，Steven。

191
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:17,880
I'm so happy to hear that.
听到这个我很高兴。

192
00:07:17,880 --> 00:07:19,960
I know we belong together.
我知道我们属于彼此。

193
00:07:19,960 --> 00:07:25,680
I love you so much.
我太爱你了。

194
00:07:25,680 --> 00:07:31,040
That was a little bit more clear this time, but now I want to look at some phrases in
这次清楚多了，但现在我想看看对话中的一些短语，

195
00:07:31,040 --> 00:07:36,440
the dialogue and see how they can be put together.
看看它们是如何组合在一起的。

196
00:07:36,440 --> 00:07:38,760
Putting it together.
组合起来。

197
00:07:38,760 --> 00:07:44,880
So Veronica apologized to Steven for getting him worked up over nothing.
所以Veronica为让Steven白激动了一场而道歉。

198
00:07:44,880 --> 00:07:45,880
Over nothing.
白费。

199
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:46,880
Over nothing.
白费。

200
00:07:46,880 --> 00:07:48,400
Now it's the complete sentence.
现在这是完整的句子。

201
00:07:48,400 --> 00:07:51,920
I'm sorry for getting you worked up over nothing.
抱歉让你白激动一场。

202
00:07:51,920 --> 00:07:54,680
So over nothing means for no reason, right?
所以“over nothing”就是“无缘无故”的意思，对吧？

203
00:07:54,680 --> 00:07:55,680
Right, exactly.
对，没错。

204
00:07:55,680 --> 00:08:01,600
So why don't we listen to some other examples of how we can use over nothing.
那我们不如听一些其他例子，看看怎么用“over nothing”。

205
00:08:01,600 --> 00:08:04,680
Example one.
例子一。

206
00:08:04,680 --> 00:08:07,040
You always get angry over nothing.
你总是无缘无故生气。

207
00:08:07,040 --> 00:08:11,640
You have such a bad temper.
你脾气真差。

208
00:08:11,640 --> 00:08:15,320
Example two.
例子二。

209
00:08:15,320 --> 00:08:17,480
I called the police last night over nothing.
我昨晚无缘无故报了警。

210
00:08:17,480 --> 00:08:22,280
I thought I had a thief in my house.
我以为家里进了贼。

211
00:08:22,280 --> 00:08:23,280
Example three.
例子三。

212
00:08:23,280 --> 00:08:27,000
Let's not fight over nothing.
我们别为小事吵架。

213
00:08:27,000 --> 00:08:30,880
Let's just have dinner in peace.
咱们安安静静吃顿饭吧。

214
00:08:30,880 --> 00:08:35,560
Okay so we see you can use many different verbs together with over nothing.
好的，所以我们看到你可以把很多不同的动词和“over nothing”搭配使用。

215
00:08:35,560 --> 00:08:41,160
So get excited over nothing, get angry over nothing, get upset over nothing.
比如无缘无故兴奋、无缘无故生气、无缘无故难过。

216
00:08:41,160 --> 00:08:42,160
Exactly.
没错。

217
00:08:42,160 --> 00:08:43,160
Very good.
很好。

218
00:08:43,160 --> 00:08:44,160
So over nothing.
所以是“over nothing”。

219
00:08:44,160 --> 00:08:46,140
And now for our next phrase.
现在来看下一个短语。

220
00:08:46,140 --> 00:08:52,040
So when Steven was telling Veronica how much he loved her, he told her, not a day has
当史蒂文告诉维罗妮卡他有多爱她时，他说，

221
00:08:52,040 --> 00:08:54,840
gone by when I haven't thought of you.
没有一天我不在想你。

222
00:08:54,840 --> 00:08:57,960
So not a day has gone by.
所以是“not a day has gone by”。

223
00:08:57,960 --> 00:09:02,200
So that part of the sentence, not a day has gone by, what does he mean by that?
那么句子里的这部分，“not a day has gone by”，他是什么意思呢？

224
00:09:02,200 --> 00:09:05,640
He means basically every day I think of you.
他基本上是说每一天我都在想你。

225
00:09:05,640 --> 00:09:08,600
There hasn't been a moment where I haven't thought of you.
没有一刻我不在想你。

226
00:09:08,600 --> 00:09:10,320
Now how can we change it a little bit?
那我们怎么稍微改一下呢？

227
00:09:10,320 --> 00:09:12,000
What can we change within this phrase?
这个短语里我们能改什么？

228
00:09:12,000 --> 00:09:14,640
Well, you can put in different times.
嗯，你可以放不同的时间。

229
00:09:14,640 --> 00:09:20,600
So not a day has gone by, not an hour has gone by, not a moment has gone by.
所以没有一天过去，没有一小时过去，没有一刻过去。

230
00:09:20,600 --> 00:09:22,840
Not a month, not a year.
没有一个月，没有一年。

231
00:09:22,840 --> 00:09:23,840
Exactly.
没错。

232
00:09:23,840 --> 00:09:26,000
So you can use different times in that phrase.
所以你可以在这个短语里用不同的时间。

233
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:30,880
But an important thing is that the complement is always negative, right?
但重要的一点是，后面的部分总是否定的，对吧？

234
00:09:30,880 --> 00:09:31,880
That's right.
对。

235
00:09:31,880 --> 00:09:33,540
So it's always followed by a negative.
所以它后面总是跟一个否定句。

236
00:09:33,540 --> 00:09:37,960
Not a day has gone by that I haven't wished you were here.
没有一天过去我不希望你在这里。

237
00:09:37,960 --> 00:09:39,880
So it's followed by a negative.
所以后面跟否定句。

238
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:40,880
That's right.
没错。

239
00:09:40,880 --> 00:09:42,240
Maybe one more.
也许再来一个。

240
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:47,120
Not a second has gone by that I haven't missed you.
没有一秒钟过去我不在想你。

241
00:09:47,120 --> 00:09:48,120
Very good examples.
非常好的例子。

242
00:09:48,120 --> 00:09:49,120
Very romantic.
非常浪漫。

243
00:09:49,120 --> 00:09:50,120
Oh Marco.
哦，马可。

244
00:09:50,120 --> 00:09:51,120
Yeah.
是的。

245
00:09:51,120 --> 00:09:52,120
All right.
好了。

246
00:09:52,120 --> 00:09:53,400
And now our last phrase.
现在是我们最后一个短语。

247
00:09:53,400 --> 00:09:57,580
He told her I'll always be here for you no matter what.
他告诉她：“无论发生什么，我都会一直在这里陪着你。”

248
00:09:57,580 --> 00:09:59,040
No matter what.
无论发生什么。

249
00:09:59,040 --> 00:10:00,040
No matter what.
无论发生什么。

250
00:10:00,040 --> 00:10:01,040
No matter what.
无论发生什么。

251
00:10:01,040 --> 00:10:02,040
What does he mean by that?
他这么说是什么意思？

252
00:10:02,040 --> 00:10:06,160
Well, regardless of or you know, nothing's going to stop me.
嗯，意思是“不管怎样”，或者你知道的，没有什么能阻止我。

253
00:10:06,160 --> 00:10:07,160
Okay.
好的。

254
00:10:07,160 --> 00:10:11,360
So if I want to get that job, I'm going to get it no matter what.
所以如果我想得到那份工作，无论如何我都会得到它。

255
00:10:11,360 --> 00:10:12,800
So nothing's going to stop you.
所以没有什么能阻止你。

256
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:16,760
